ine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge intestine\u003C/strong\u003E has the highest microbial load in the human body, with approximately 10^12 bacteria per gram of content. This is due to the favourable environment for bacterial growth, including a stable temperature, pH, and nutrient availability. The \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach\u003C/strong\u003E has a relatively low bacterial load due to its acidic environment (pH 1.5-3.5). The \u003Cstrong\u003Emouth\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Enose\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ethroat\u003C/strong\u003E have intermediate bacterial loads but significantly less than the large intestine due to less favourable conditions for bacterial proliferation and the presence of protective mechanisms like mucus and antimicrobial proteins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The large intestine has the highest microbial load in the human body, containing approximately 10^12 bacteria per gram.","The human microbiome varies in composition and density across different body sites."],"references":["Dupont HL, Jiang ZD, Dupont AW, Utay NS. THE INTESTINAL MICROBIOME IN HUMAN HEALTH AND DISEASE. Trans Am Clin Climatol Assoc. 2020;131:178-197. PMID: 32675857; PMCID: PMC7358474.","Valdes AM, Walter J, Segal E, Spector TD. Role of the gut microbiota in nutrition and health. BMJ. 2018 Jun 13;361:k2179. doi: 10.1136/bmj.k2179. PMID: 29899036; PMCID: PMC6000740.","Haller, D. (Ed.). (2018). The gut microbiome in health and disease. Springer."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48343"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48343"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T10:38:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T10:39:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item